---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Offdesk Morning Review Workflow - Forager"
  description="Use Forager to plan safe offdesk agent work, review overnight evidence, approve recovery actions, and promote adaptive wiki knowledge only after inspection."
>
  <Nav />

  <article class="pt-32 pb-16 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose-content">
      <header class="mb-12">
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-white mb-6 leading-tight">Offdesk Morning Review Workflow</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Forager is not only a session manager. It is a safe loop for handing work to AI agents while you are away, then reviewing durable evidence before the next decision.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section>
        <h2>The Loop</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Ondesk planning:</strong> create focused sessions, isolate branches with worktrees, and decide which tasks are safe to run unattended.</li>
          <li><strong>Offdesk execution:</strong> queue durable tasks behind approval gates, provider fallback checks, recovery records, and audit trails.</li>
          <li><strong>Morning review:</strong> inspect task status, background probes, debug bundles, maintenance reports, Council decisions, and result artifacts.</li>
          <li><strong>Knowledge promotion:</strong> promote adaptive wiki candidates only after reviewing evidence, counterexamples, scope, and freshness.</li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>What to Check First</h2>
        <p>
          Start with the high-signal surfaces before opening individual agent terminals:
        </p>
        <pre><code>forager status
forager offdesk tasks --json
forager offdesk pending --json
forager offdesk maintenance-report --json</code></pre>
        <p>
          These commands answer the operational questions: what ran, what is waiting, what failed, what needs recovery, and what requires explicit approval.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Adaptive Wiki Review</h2>
        <p>
          Overnight runs may create wiki candidates or provisional trial entries. They should not silently become future instructions. Review them as evidence-backed proposals:
        </p>
        <pre><code>forager offdesk wiki candidates --json
forager offdesk wiki lint --json
forager offdesk wiki review --json
forager offdesk wiki export-markdown --output ./adaptive-wiki-review</code></pre>
        <p>
          The canonical source remains the Forager profile state. Markdown exports are human review snapshots, not writable truth.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Decision Rules</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Do not claim completion unless a result artifact, task status, or test output proves it.</li>
          <li>Do not let wiki context change commands, workdirs, provider choices, models, or approvals.</li>
          <li>Use Council output as a read-only recommendation, not as permission to mutate state.</li>
          <li>Convert failures into recovery tasks, maintenance requests, or revised plans instead of silent retries.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Prepare the Next Run</h2>
        <p>
          A good night run starts from the morning review. Pick one narrow goal, define stop conditions, choose the agent modes involved, and queue only the work that has the required approvals and evidence boundaries.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>

  <Footer />
</Base>
